{
  "doc_id": "40790",
  "text": "HS-toxin, also known as helminthosporoside, is produced by Bipolaris sacchari (also known as H. saccahri or Drechslera sacchari), the causal agent of the eyespot disease of sugarcane. HS-toxin consists of four b-1,5-linked galactofuranose units linked with the asymmetric sesquiterpene core (C 15 H 24 O 2 ) at carbon positions 2 and 13 ( Fig. 1 ; [CITATION_1] . HS-toxin causes lesions and electrolyte leakage only on sugarcane cultivars susceptible to B. sacchari and thus can be considered as a HST [CITATION_2] . Membrane depolarization is also observed as a result of its activity, an effect that is reversible by increasing temperature at 30°C or higher [CITATION_3] . However, although a good correlation between sensitivity to the toxin and susceptibility to the pathogen is in general observed, other factors might be contributing to the disease as well, because in some cases, disease severity did not correlate with sensitivity to the toxin [CITATION_4] . In addition to HS-toxin, B. sacchari can produce lower molecular weight toxinanalogs (toxoids) that lack one or more of the galactose residues and act antagonistically to the HS-toxin, thus protecting sensitive tissues against the toxin [CITATION_5] . The biological relevance of the production of these analogs by the fungus is not understood yet, but their production could suggest that they interact or compete for the yet to be identified HS-toxin receptor.",
